{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646235"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:27:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:27:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18163"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18163"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.23,0.1,0.6,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75001"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10877"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60507"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7383"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25301"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75001"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EShoulder arthritis commonly affects the glenohumeral joint and can significantly impact daily activities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a common symptom of shoulder arthritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Swelling of the entire arm","Redness and warmth over the shoulder","Sharp, shooting pain down the arm","Grinding sensation in the joint","Numbness in the fingers"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egrinding sensation in the joint\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic symptom of shoulder arthritis. This occurs due to the degeneration of articular cartilage leading to bone-on-bone contact during shoulder movement. The grinding or crepitus sensation is often accompanied by pain and stiffness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther symptoms suggested in the options are not typical of shoulder arthritis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwelling of the entire arm\u003C/strong\u003E suggests lymphatic or vascular pathology\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERedness and warmth over the shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E indicates acute inflammation or infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESharp, shooting pain down the arm\u003C/strong\u003E is more consistent with nerve compression or cervical radiculopathy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumbness in the fingers\u003C/strong\u003E suggests a neurological condition such as peripheral neuropathy or cervical nerve root compression\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShoulder arthritis typically causes localised symptoms in the glenohumeral joint including pain that worsens with activity, morning stiffness, and decreased range of motion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A grinding or crepitus sensation during shoulder movement is a characteristic sign of shoulder arthritis due to cartilage degeneration.","Shoulder arthritis primarily causes localised joint symptoms rather than neurological or vascular manifestations.","Key features of shoulder arthritis include pain, stiffness, and reduced range of motion in the glenohumeral joint."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60507"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18163"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60507"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T20:10:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T20:11:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10877"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75001"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship